post_text:
BRONC FANS -

We love posting weekly schedules of our Broncs' athletic events. Unfortunately, with the current situation, it could be a full-time job keeping up with schedule changes and restrictions in other school districts, and we don't want to misinform anybody. We strongly encourage you to reach out to family members of athletes about their schedules and restrictions. Our coaches will be keeping them informed of changes and developments. We also encourage you to look at events posted on NFHS Network. You will find many frosh/JV/varsity soccer, volleyball and football games will be live streamed. There is an annual or monthly subscription, but just look at it as gas money and admittance fees saved! Some of Frenchtown's local establishments will also be streaming games, so check their Facebook pages as well. We will do our best to share NFHS links on the day of games as a reminder to watch & support your Broncs from wherever you might be!!! 🧡🖤🧡

https://bit.ly/2YMkBgD

post_text:
Via Frenchtown School District:

The Frenchtown School District has been given the following directive/order from the Missoula County Health Department regarding spectators at events:

Football- 2 tickets per player on the field (the number of players has also been limited by the county)
Cheerleading- 2 tickets per cheerleader on the sideline.
*No other spectators will be allowed.
**There will not be any out of district spectators permitted on campus.

Soccer, Volleyball, XC and Golf have been capped at 250 spectators.

Please help us comply with the order. We are pleased they are letting us play and allowing some parents to watch but we hope with time the restrictions placed upon us by the county will be eased and the entire Bronc Family will be able to enjoy Frenchtown activities.

**We are working on ways to stream the events live through the National Federation of High School Network.

Thank you for your cooperation!

GO BRONCS! 🧡🖤🧡

MHSA released its guidelines to return to fall activities this morning. The "resumption of sports and other activities is crucial to the growth, development and mental and emotional wellness of our Montana youth."

Golf practices are scheduled to begin on Thursday, Aug. 13, while football, volleyball, soccer and cross country will begin the following day. Golf tournaments can be held on Saturday, Aug. 15, while the other sports can hold competitions on Thursday, Aug. 27.

YEARBOOKS!
For the 2019-2020 school year, the Frenchtown High School yearbook is switched to a spring delivery! Yearbooks will be arriving to the high school office at the end of May instead of in the fall. If you have purchased a yearbook you can come and pick them up in the high school office and if you haven’t no worries, because you can purchase a yearbook from this and previous years in the office or you can go to Yearbookforever.com and order this year’s book online. The yearbook staff students did a great job helping to capture the moments and memories from the school year and get a copy for your student so they can look back on another great school year. This year’s book is on sale for $55 and previous year’s books can be purchased for a reduced rate. Thank you and Go Broncs!!

- Mr. Mac

post_text:
Congrats to Coach Normand on his retirement! Thank you for all you've done for the Frenchtown community & students. ENJOY! 🧡🖤

"I want to inform everyone that I will be retiring from Frenchtown High School after thirty-six years of teaching and coaching. I can’t believe how fast the time has gone by. It has been a great honor to serve the Frenchtown School District, community and students. I have been very lucky to work with so many outstanding staff members, students and athletes over the years. A special thanks for all the athletes who have worked so hard and made it possible for me to look forward to practice every day over the years. Frenchtown has been a very special place to spend my teaching and coaching years. This isn’t how I pictured my last season of coaching and teaching as a Bronc, but I feel honored in walking out the doors of Frenchtown High School for the last time with an exceptional and extraordinary senior class. Thanks Frenchtown!!! GoBroncs

Coach Normand"

Frenchtown Bronc Cross Country/Track

Wrestling

Frenchtown downed Florence 65-12 in dual behind five pins and a technical fall. Smokey Stoker, Peyton Hicks, Noah Rausch, Canyon Shope all had pins for the Broncs. Tate Jones also had a technical fall.

Frenchtown finished off the Frenchtown Quad with a 57-3 win over Corvallis. Landen Stewart started things off with a 45 second pin, which Eli Warner followed up on with a 19-3 technical fall. Walker Dyer and Jake Bibler each had major decisions for the Broncs, while Carson Pyron, Noah Rausch, Canyon Shope and Tate Jones all had falls. The lone Blue Devil win was a 9-3 decision by Triston Davis over Smokey Stoker.

post_text:
Frenchtown downed the Whitefish Bulldogs 50-15. Landen Stewart (113), Roman Duke (126), Smokey Stoker (145), and Canyon Shope (205) recorded pins for the Broncs. Eli Warner recorded a 9-0 major decision, while Noah Rausch also added on bonus points with a 12-3 major decision.

Smokey Stoker and Zane Schroeder each recorded falls as Frenchtown took down Lake City, Idaho, 38-35 on Wednesday night. Eli Warner added a decision win, and John Warner was able to get a technical fall to round out the non-forfeit winners for the Broncs.

Hank Rugg was also in double figures for the Broncs, scoring 15. Cole Truman had 28 points for the Beavers.
